00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:13,120
Second issue is the issue of community, about whether each person can believe in God on his or her own without any community support and without any objective evidence or not.

2
00:00:13,440 --> 00:00:26,160
The Protestant view of community is that an individual's faith isn't based on any objective evidence and doesn't have any correlation with anybody else's beliefs or faith.

3
00:00:26,160 --> 00:00:28,641
Each has their own faith.

4
00:00:28,641 --> 00:00:31,840
Luther said, each man is a pope.

5
00:00:31,840 --> 00:00:35,601
Kierkegaard said, each person is alone before God.

6
00:00:36,081 --> 00:00:41,241
And Kierkegaard said, Christianity has no objective validity.

7
00:00:41,241 --> 00:00:46,440
And Dostoevsky is on this very Kierkegaardian wavelength.

8
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:49,480
He knows what this view looks like.

9
00:00:49,481 --> 00:00:53,480
Remember, Kierkegaard says Abraham is in total isolation.

10
00:00:53,480 --> 00:00:55,480
He is on a lonely path.

11
00:00:55,480 --> 00:01:02,120
He can't explain to himself or anyone else, or he can't explain to anyone, even himself, what he's doing.

12
00:01:02,761 --> 00:01:10,920
And that certainly is a Kierkegaardian Protestant Lutheran view.

13
00:01:11,881 --> 00:01:31,240
And it finally leads to Kierkegaard attacking Lutheran Church for providing a herd or a community to protect people from the hard task of having faith all by themselves in isolation, even in opposition to the intelligibility and to the ethical.

14
00:01:31,241 --> 00:01:54,920
But what I want to quote this time, because it sounds so much like the Christ of the Grand Inquisitor story, something from Kierkegaard's attack on Christendom, which was his last book, his actual critic attack on the Lutheran Church as standing sort of between people, preventing people from being Christians.

15
00:01:54,920 --> 00:02:00,441
He says, the spiritual man differs from us men in being able to endure isolation.

16
00:02:00,441 --> 00:02:09,001
His rank as a spiritual man is proportionate to his strength for enduring isolation, whereas we men are constantly in need of the others, the herd.

17
00:02:09,001 --> 00:02:14,361
That's the Grand Inquisitor calls us the ante, the others, the herd.

18
00:02:14,361 --> 00:02:21,321
We die or despair if we're not reassured by being in the herd, of the same opinion as the herd, etc.

19
00:02:21,641 --> 00:02:29,121
But the Christianity of the New Testament is precisely reckoned upon and related to the isolation of the spiritual man.

20
00:02:29,441 --> 00:02:41,521
Christianity in the New Testament consists in loving God in hatred to man, in hatred to oneself, and thereby of other men, hating father, mother, one's own child, wife, etc.

21
00:02:41,761 --> 00:02:44,961
The strongest expression for the most agonizing isolation.

22
00:02:44,961 --> 00:02:46,561
It's really incredible.

23
00:02:46,560 --> 00:02:57,840
I mean, he gets this from these passages where Jesus' family comes around and he interrupts him when he's going about his preaching and he says, and they say, your mother and brother and sisters are here.

24
00:02:57,840 --> 00:03:00,481
And he says, I don't have any mother, brothers, or sisters.

25
00:03:00,480 --> 00:03:04,081
So Kierkegaard is making that very central.

26
00:03:04,081 --> 00:03:04,880
So I'll go on.

27
00:03:04,881 --> 00:03:08,000
The strongest expression of the most agonizing isolation.

28
00:03:08,001 --> 00:03:14,321
And it is in view of this, I say, that such men, men of this quality and caliber, are not born anymore.

29
00:03:14,321 --> 00:03:22,800
Just like the Grand Inquisitor saying, you know, I can go alone and live in isolation for years on berries in the wilderness, that very few people can do that.

30
00:03:22,800 --> 00:03:31,840
And you get the impression that nobody can do it now, except maybe Father Farrapont, who thinks he's the only one who can give up his bread and who's completely crazy.

31
00:03:32,961 --> 00:03:37,360
If there aren't any sane ascetics, they don't seem to be around anymore.

32
00:03:37,680 --> 00:03:43,840
So the Jesus figure then says that you have to be able to live in this kind of isolation.

33
00:03:43,840 --> 00:03:46,480
And the Grand Inquisitor says it's impossible.

34
00:03:46,800 --> 00:03:48,641
Human beings can't do that.

35
00:03:48,641 --> 00:03:54,000
We'll provide community comfort by way of the church.

36
00:03:54,001 --> 00:04:14,680
So otherwise, people will become dangerous because, and we're seeing it happening right now, they get into sectarian fights in which they're killing each other because each one of them thinks that they've got the one truth that is supposed to, that really applies to everybody.

37
00:04:15,480 --> 00:04:23,081
Dostoevsky is saying this on 247 near the top, about eight lines down.

38
00:04:23,081 --> 00:04:31,720
For these pitiful creatures are concerned not only to find something that all would believe in and worship, what is essential is that all may be together in it.

39
00:04:31,720 --> 00:04:39,480
The craving for community of worship is the chief misery of every man individually and of all humanity from the beginning of time.

40
00:04:39,480 --> 00:04:43,401
For the sake of common worship, they've slain each other with the sword.

41
00:04:43,401 --> 00:04:45,961
That seems true.

42
00:04:45,961 --> 00:04:49,561
The Grand Inquisitor seems something there.

43
00:04:49,881 --> 00:05:01,160
And the Grand Inquisitor says the only answer to this absolute need, this craving of all human beings, is to set up one universal church, Christendom.

44
00:05:01,160 --> 00:05:15,641
You just go out with your crusades and your missionaries, and you finally make the whole world Christian, and then everybody stops killing everybody else, and everybody's happy because they've all found one shared truth they can all believe in.

45
00:05:15,641 --> 00:05:19,881
That's what the Grand Inquisitor has done, or is on the way to doing.

46
00:05:19,881 --> 00:05:28,601
