Next issue is the morality issue.

69
00:07:09,920 --> 00:07:15,280
That has lots of different sub-issues, you can see from the chart that we've been looking at.

70
00:07:15,680 --> 00:07:21,121
And they are confession, miracles, mystery, and authority.

71
00:07:21,280 --> 00:07:26,160
There's a lot to be said about each of them, at least a lot to be said about two of them.

72
00:07:26,160 --> 00:07:27,681
So let's start.

73
00:07:27,680 --> 00:07:28,881
Confession.

74
00:07:28,881 --> 00:07:33,040
That's going to turn out to be a wonderful one for demagicalizing.

75
00:07:33,200 --> 00:07:35,761
We have to first just state the issue.

76
00:07:36,160 --> 00:07:37,360
So here's confession.

77
00:07:37,361 --> 00:07:44,601
Jesus, according to the Grand Inquisitor, demands that people must get along without moral support or moral guidance.

78
00:07:44,601 --> 00:07:47,321
Kierkegaard has a similar view.

79
00:07:47,721 --> 00:08:02,601
And therefore, by the way, that means he's against confession, where you go to the priest and he tells you whether what you've done is wrong and how wrong and gives you a penance to make up for what you've done.

80
00:08:02,601 --> 00:08:09,961
All of that seems to the Grand Inquisitor to be something that Jesus is opposing.

81
00:08:09,960 --> 00:08:18,361
And Kierkegaard, speaking like Jesus, says that confession is a kind of immoral temptation.

82
00:08:18,361 --> 00:08:19,320
That's not his quote.

83
00:08:19,320 --> 00:08:20,761
I'll read you his quote.

84
00:08:20,761 --> 00:08:29,161
He says, every human being is gloriously constituted, again from the attack on Christendom, every human being is gloriously constituted.

85
00:08:29,160 --> 00:08:38,761
But what ruins so many is, among other things, all this wretched tittle-tattle between man and man about that which should be suffered and matured in silence.

86
00:08:39,560 --> 00:08:43,001
If you've done something wrong, then you should realize it's wrong.

87
00:08:43,001 --> 00:08:51,241
And when you realize it's wrong, you have to have this inner suffering where you punish yourself.

88
00:08:51,560 --> 00:09:05,881
This confession before, then Kierkegaard's against this confession before men instead of before God, this hardy communication between this man and that about what ought to be secret and exist only before God in secrecy.

89
00:09:05,881 --> 00:09:10,121
This impatient craving for intermediary consolation.

90
00:09:10,440 --> 00:09:16,280
So that now, but and Jesus says, we're not going to satisfy that.

91
00:09:16,280 --> 00:09:21,001
We're going to demand that people not get that kind of confidence.

92
00:09:21,001 --> 00:09:34,960
So let's hope it's on 248 at the top, about four lines down.

93
00:09:34,960 --> 00:09:44,481
In place of the rigid ancient law, man must hereafter, with free heart, decide for himself what is good and evil, having only thy image before him as his guide.

94
00:09:44,481 --> 00:09:53,040
But that's what the Grand Inquisitor says, Jesus says, and that's what the Grand Inquisitor says people can't put up with.

95
00:09:53,040 --> 00:09:57,841
They have to be told, they have to be given guidance to what's good and evil.

96
00:09:57,841 --> 00:10:00,641
They have to confess when they've done something evil.

97
00:10:00,641 --> 00:10:02,800
And he's got it close.

98
00:10:02,800 --> 00:10:14,801
I mean, Roman Catholicism certainly puts confession, individual confession between an individual and the priest, and as an important, I think, called sacrament.

99
00:10:16,481 --> 00:10:26,081
And so you get the Grand Inquisitor saying on 252 how he's going to deal with it in the middle.

100
00:10:26,080 --> 00:10:28,321
And they will have no secrets from us.

101
00:10:28,320 --> 00:10:39,521
We shall allow or forbid them to live with their wives and mistresses, to have or have not have children, according to whether they have been obedient or disobedient, and they will submit to us gladly and cheerfully.

102
00:10:39,521 --> 00:10:48,241
The most painful, this is the confession part, the most painful secrets of their conscience, all, all they will bring to us, and we shall have an answer for all.

103
00:10:48,401 --> 00:10:58,161
They will be glad to believe our answer, for it will save them from the great fear and terrible agony that they endure at present in making a free decision for themselves.

104
00:10:59,440 --> 00:11:02,081
So that's the Grand Inquisitor's side.

105
00:11:02,401 --> 00:11:09,961
The Protestant side is Jesus precisely did what the Grand Inquisitor said he did.

106
00:11:10,280 --> 00:11:23,321
That is, he said he was replacing the Hebrew law or fulfilling it anyway, claiming that you had to decide for yourself what was okay to do on the Sabbath and what was not, for instance.

107
00:11:23,320 --> 00:11:33,161
And there was no general, once you get rid of the law, then you have to, as Augustine said, love and do what you will.

108
00:11:33,160 --> 00:11:38,121
That is, your only guideline is going to be your own feelings.

109
00:11:38,920 --> 00:11:45,961
That's the Protestant view, all right, and that's the view the Grand Inquisitor attributes to Jesus.

110
00:11:45,960 --> 00:11:53,801
There's no public justification for moral beliefs, and you could recognize that as the suspension of the ethical.

111
00:11:53,800 --> 00:11:58,201
Every individual is higher than the universal.

112
00:11:58,200 --> 00:12:00,280
Every individual has their own right.

113
00:12:01,320 --> 00:12:09,481
Abraham has some kind of duty and rightness being what, from the public point of view, is a murderer.

114
00:12:09,481 --> 00:12:24,601
And that's the, and there's, and you'll only make, you can make life a lot easier for people if you take that away, but that's the highest Christian demand, the Dostoevsky Jesus says.

115
00:12:24,601 --> 00:12:26,681
Now, remember, don't get lost.

116
00:12:26,680 --> 00:12:30,121
In each of these cases, we are always having an antinomy.

117
00:12:30,121 --> 00:12:34,040
There is the extreme Roman Catholic version.

118
00:12:34,040 --> 00:13:06,241
Every person gets moral guidelines, gets confessing, gets forgiven, and so forth by the church, which has a universal ethics and knows what's right and wrong, on the one hand, which seems unacceptable, and on the other hand, Kierkegaard-like, total freedom, suspending the ethical, everybody doing what they are called to do, and which is unintelligible and goes against the moral standards and can't be confessed to anybody because they wouldn't understand it, and so forth.

119
00:13:06,241 --> 00:13:12,881
Okay, and the question, of course, again, don't get lost, is there must be some third way if it's an antinomy.

120
00:13:12,881 --> 00:13:24,241
And if this, and if there's one piece missing, remember, we're going back and forth between what the Protestant Lutheran view and the Roman Catholic view, just so I want to make sure you're all with it.

121
00:13:24,241 --> 00:13:27,681
What's the third view that we're not at yet?

