138
00:14:31,440 --> 00:14:42,680
The question of miracles is whether people could keep their faith freely without miracles, or must people have miracles, suspension of physical laws, to believe in God.

139
00:14:43,000 --> 00:14:59,081
So the question, the temptation to Jesus was that he would perform a miracle, throw himself down from the tem top of the temple and show people how he wouldn't get hurt, how the angels would catch him and cushion his fall, and that would in effect force them all to believe in him.

140
00:14:59,081 --> 00:15:03,160
Who could resist when you get a demonstration like that?

141
00:15:03,160 --> 00:15:10,041
And that's what people absolutely need.

142
00:15:10,361 --> 00:15:33,480
On 248, about three-quarters of the way down, the Grand Inquisitor says, is the nature of men such that they can reject miracles at the same moments of their, at the great moments of their life, the moments of their deepest and most agonizing spiritual difficulties, cling only to the free verdict of the heart.

143
00:15:33,480 --> 00:15:36,280
So that's a question.

144
00:15:36,281 --> 00:15:57,641
Can people, the best people, but normal people, not people like the Grand Inquisitor, can ordinary people live without miracles to give without having a religion that they are forced to believe in because it performs miracles?

145
00:15:57,641 --> 00:15:58,920
That's the question.

146
00:15:58,920 --> 00:16:04,440
The interesting thing is to see whether Dostoevsky thinks people can live without miracles.

147
00:16:04,440 --> 00:16:10,521
If he thinks they can, can't, then how is he going to put in, how's he going to show a miracle?

148
00:16:10,520 --> 00:16:12,520
